In determining the meaning of any Act of Congress, unless the context
indicates otherwise—

words importing the singular include and apply to several persons, parties, or
things;

words importing the plural include the singular;

words importing the masculine gender include the feminine as well;

words used in the present tense include the future as well as the present;

the words “insane” and “insane person” shall include every idiot, insane
person, and person non compos mentis;

the words “person” and “whoever” include corporations, companies,
associations, firms, partnerships, societies, and joint stock companies, as
well as individuals;

“officer” includes any person authorized by law to perform the duties of the
office;

“signature” or “subscription” includes a mark when the person making the same
intended it as such;

“oath” includes affirmation, and “sworn” includes affirmed;

“writing” includes printing and typewriting and reproductions of visual
symbols by photographing, multigraphing, mimeographing, manifolding, or
otherwise.

(July 30, 1947, ch. 388, 61 Stat. 633; June 25, 1948, ch. 645, § 6, 62 Stat.
859; Oct. 31, 1951, ch. 655, § 1, 65 Stat. 710; Pub. L. 112–231, § 2(a), Dec.
28, 2012, 126 Stat. 1619.)
